Section2.Para:
The NEM-weighted average emissions intensity is approximately 0.94 tCO2/MWh (ABARES 2011a, b);

The average emission intensity in Europe is around 0.35; in the US is 0.54; and in Canada about 0.18 tCO2/MWh.
                   however, emission intensities vary significantly across the NEM. For instance, Victoria has the highest emission intensity of about 1.18 tCO2/MWh, reflecting the relatively high concentration of brown coal-fired generation; while Tasmania has the lowest rate of around 0.06 tCO2/MWh due to the predominance of hydro plants in that state (AEMO 2013a). According to the Treasury model, the CPM was expected to reduce the average emission intensity of the electricity sector by 77 % over the period to 2050 and result in a cumulative reduction in pollution from this sector of almost 500 MtCO2e by 2030 (Treasury 2011). Emissions reduction in the power sector was expected to occur mainly through switching from the dominant coal-fired electricity generation to existing lower-emission alternatives (natural gas or renewable energy) due to the rising cost of generating electricity by coal. However, the displacement of coal by existing renewable or gas generators depends on a number of factors, such as the price of natural gas, the availability of renewable energy sources and, most importantly, carbon costs pass-through rate (CPTR). The significant levels of the CPTRs indicate that the incremental increases in revenue associated with the carbon price-induced increases in wholesale electricity prices will be enough to offset the incremental increases in variable costs associated with the imposition of the carbon price. In this case, carbon costs are unlikely to be borne by generators. In contrast, low levels of CPTRs are indicative of generators that are bearing a higher proportion of the incidence of carbon costs, which could result in the current methods being replaced by more carbon-efficient technologies (in addition to other factors that may affect this replacement).
